25|$|Functions {{that are}} {{localized}} {{in the time}} domain have Fourier transforms that are spread out across the frequency domain and vice versa, a phenomenon known as the uncertainty principle. The critical case for this principle is the <b>Gaussian</b> <b>function,</b> of substantial importance in probability theory and statistics {{as well as in}} the study of physical phenomena exhibiting normal distribution (e.g., diffusion). The Fourier transform of a <b>Gaussian</b> <b>function</b> is another <b>Gaussian</b> <b>function.</b> Joseph Fourier introduced the transform in his study of heat transfer, where Gaussian functions appear as solutions of the heat equation.|$|E
25|$|Discretization is {{typically}} achieved by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel at discrete points, normally at positions {{corresponding to the}} midpoints of each pixel. This reduces the computational cost but, for very small filter kernels, point sampling the <b>Gaussian</b> <b>function</b> with very few samples leads to a large error. In these cases, accuracy is maintained (at a slight computational cost) by integration of the <b>Gaussian</b> <b>function</b> over each pixel's area.|$|E
